The paper deals with codes on graphs, which are often studied in the information theory community, hence cs.IT is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves convolutional codes, which are a type of error-correcting codes, and hence cs.DS (discrete structures) is also a likely sub-category. The paper also involves group codes, which are studied in the context of algebraic coding theory, and hence cs.SI (symbolic computation) and cs.CC (computational complexity) are also likely sub-categories. Finally, the paper involves sum-product update rules, which are often used in optimization algorithms, and hence cs.NA (numerical analysis) is also a possible sub-category.
